Stay at home
Only go outside for food, health reasons or work (but only if you cannot work from home)
If you go out, stay 2 metres (6ft) away from other people at all times
Wash your hands as soon as you get home
Do not meet others, even friends or family.
You can spread the virus even if you don’t have symptoms.

Cases of coronavirus (COVID-19) have been confirmed in Peru. The Peruvian authorities have introduced measures to limit the spread of the virus.
On 15 March, Peru announced a national State of Emergency, which has now been extended until 26 April.
Since 31 March, there is a nationwide curfew between the hours of 18:00 to 05:00. In Tumbes, Piura, Lambayeque, La Libertad and Loreto the curfew will start two hours early, lasting from 16:00 to 05:00. The Government of Peru has announced that all individuals should use facemasks when going outside.
From 3 April, further restrictions were applied nationwide. The measures stated that on Mondays, Wednesdays and Fridays, only men would be allowed out of their homes; on Tuesdays, Thursdays and Saturdays, only women would be allowed out of their homes. On Sundays, no one would be allowed out of their homes. On 8 April, the Peruvian authorities announced that these gender-specific restrictions on movement will be lifted from 13 April, after which men and women will be allowed to leave home for urgent issues on any day Monday - Saturday. The Sunday curfew remains.
On 9 and 10 April, there will be an additional nationwide full-day curfew for both men and women. You will not be allowed out of your homes or accommodation on these days. These restrictions will not apply to those who have been in touch with the British Embassy to obtain a travel permit (salvo-conducto) in order to travel to flights or on pre-arranged transport.
Borders and travel restrictions
All borders are closed until at least 26 April.
Peru announced a ban on all flights arriving from and departing to Europe and Asia, with effect from Monday 16 March. The ban is for 30 days and could be extended.
If you’re in Peru, you’re advised to secure accommodation for this period. IPERU, the Peruvian Tourism Information Agency, is offering details of suitable accommodation. There are reports of hotels and hostels closing throughout the country due to threats of quarantine. IPERU has details of remaining accommodation options. If you change accommodation, please make sure that you send these changes to lima.escalations@fco.gov.uk.
If you wish to leave Peru, see Return to the UK
Local measures
Freedom of movement is restricted for the same period. The main exceptions are to purchase food or medication, or to visit banks. British nationals in Peru should follow the advice of the Peruvian authorities and abide by the measures in place. There will be police and armed forces patrols to impose the restrictions.
The Peruvian authorities have confirmed that drinking in public areas is prohibited during the State of Emergency. On 30 March, the President declared further measures to be enforced during the State of Emergency period. These include an extended mandatory curfew from 31 March between the hours of 18:00 and 05:00 each day (with exceptions for emergencies) and the complete ban of private vehicles from 05:00 on 19 March.
In Tumbes, Piura, Lambayeque, La Libertad and Loreto, the curfew will start two hours earlier, lasting from 16:00 to 05:00. (with exceptions for emergencies, in which case people should carry and show a white cloth). The Government of Peru has announced that all individuals should use facemasks when going outside.
From 3 April, further restrictions will be applied nationwide. The measures state that on Mondays, Wednesday and Fridays, only men will be allowed out of their homes; on Tuesdays, Thursdays and Saturdays, only women will be allowed out of their homes. On Sundays, no one will be allowed out of their homes. The restrictions will not apply to those travelling to flights or on pre-arranged transport.
Private and public school classes in Peru have been suspended until 4 May. Virtual sessions only will start from 6 April.
Visas
During this period the Peruvian authorities have also confirmed that fees will be waived for overstays on visas owing to the State of Emergency.
Further information
More information (in Spanish) is available on the Ministry of Health (Ministerio de Salud) website or by calling the 24/7 call free number 113, sending a WhatsApp message to +51 95284263 or emailing infosalud@minsa.gob.pe.
Further information on coronavirus, including advice on preparing for foreign travel and helping reduce the spread of the virus, is available from Public Health England and on the TravelHealthPro website.
